11- Wk18 Oral cavity to stomach 

Friday, September 22, 2017 

8:37 PM 

Oral cavity 

 

Development of teeth 

We have 20 deciduous (baby) teeth and 28-32 permanent teeth as adults.  

Out of the adult teeth, we have (assuming 16 total a side), 4 incisors centrally, 1 canine to each side, 2 premolars to each side and 3 molars to each side.  

 

Salivary glands 

 

-Sublingual gland 70%, innervated by facial nerve (CN VII) 

-Parotid gland 20%, innervated by glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) 

-Submandibular gland 10%, innervated by facial nerve (CN VII) 

 

Review the intrinsic and extrinsic tongue muscles. Consider the innervation of the tongue- motor control, general sensation, taste sensation 

 

 

Nerve supply for the tongue 

Motor supply: hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) except palatoglossus from vagus nerve (CN X) 

General sensation: mandibular V3 of trigeminal nerve (CN V) for anterior 2/3, glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) for posterior 1/3 and superior laryngeal nerve from vagus nerve for base of tongue 

Taste: facial nerve (CN VII) for anterior 2/3, glossopharyngeal for posterior 1/3 and superior laryngeal for base of tongue 

 

Anterior 2/3 refers to anterior to the circumvallate papillae.  

 

Oral cavity 

The side walls of the oral cavity are formed by the buccinators (cheeks). Buccinators press cheeks against the teeth, holding food in the oral cavity. The floor of the oral cavity is formed by two suprahyoid muscles: the mylohyoid and the geniohyoid.  

 

 

 

Palate 

The palate is 80% hard palate and 20% soft palate. The hard palate separates the oral cavity from the nasal cavity, and the soft palate acts as a continuation of the hard palate, functioning as a valve.  

 

Oropharynx 

 

Identify constrictor muscles of the pharynx 

 

The constrictor muscles include the superior, middle and inferior pharyngeal constrictors. The longitudinal muscles include the salpingopharyngeus, palatopharyngeus, and stylopharyngeus.  

 

 

Pathology of the piriform recesses and vallecula 

Food can get stuck in these spaces, and lead to infection + inflammation.  

 

Blood supply 

The ascending pharyngeal artery branches off the common carotid, at the same point as the branch-off of the external and internal carotids. The facial vein branches off the internal jugular vein.  

 

Innervation 

The muscles of the pharynx are innervated by the vagus nerve, with the exception of the stylopharyngeus which is innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX).  

 

Esophagus 

 

Revise the location of the esophagus 

The esophagus extends from C6 to T11, and passes through the diaphragm at T10. (IVC passes through at T8, aorta passes through at T12). 

 

Blood supply 

The cervical portion is supplied by the inferior thyroid artery, and drained by the inferior thyroid vein + left brachiocephalic vein.  

The thoracic portion is supplied by the abdominal aorta, and is drained by the accessory hemiazygous (upper left), hemiazygous (lower left), and azygous (right) veins.  

The abdominal portion is supplied by the left gastric artery and drained by the left gastric vein. 

 

Innervation 

The esophagus is innervated by the vagus nerve (esophageal plexus) and from the sympathetic trunk. 

 

Stomach 

 

Identify the cardia, cardial notch, pylorus, pyloric sphincter, fundus, body, greater curvature, and lesser curvature 

 

 

Note: the pylorus is divided into the pyloric antrum and pyloric canal. 

 

Review the mesenteric attachments- greater and lesser omentum, gastrolienal ligament, and gastrophrenic ligament 

Gastrolienal = stomach and spleen 

Gastrophrenic = stomach and diaphragm 

 

Blood supply 

Right gastric artery branches off the common hepatic artery (from celiac trunk). The left gastric artery branches off the celiac branch.  

 

The right gastro-omental artery branches off the gastroduodenal artery, which branches off the celiac trunk. The left gastro-omental artery branches off the splenic artery (from celiac trunk). 

 

Innervation 

-Parasympathetic nerve supply from vagus nerve 

-Sympathetic supply to celiac plexus to stomach, also carrying some pain fibers
